  "texts": [
    "⊑ is the identity relation;2.",
    "P = ℘(W).foot_9 For models based on Kripke frames, the forcing relation ⊩ defined in Definition 2.3 is equivalent to the standard satisfaction relation, i.e., M, x ⊩ ¬φ iff M, x ⊮ φ, and M, x ⊩ φ → ψ iff M, x ⊮ φ or M, x ⊩ ψ.",
    "Classical general frames ⟨W, {R i } i∈I, A⟩ (reviewed in Appendix § A.2) may also be regarded as partial-state frames ⟨W, ⊑, {R i } i∈I, A⟩ in which ⊑ is the identity relation.",
    "When ⊑ is identity, the closure conditions on the set P of admissible propositions in a partial-state frame coincide with the closure conditions on the set A of admissible propositions in a general frame (Definition A.5).",
    "As usual, we may view Kripke frames as full general frames, i.e., general frames in which A = ℘(W).Henceforth we will call general frames world frames."
